commentBody: I don't have an OED, but I don't think "chitling" is a legitimate word. It is actually a corruption of "chitterling," which is usually represented in the plural form "chitterlings."

Enjoyable puzzle, but didn‚Äôt understand how ONEND could be nonstop. Had to go through lots of comments before finding the explanation‚Äîthank you RAH! Makes perfect sense now, but that hadn‚Äôt occurred to me. My favorite thing about today‚Äôs puzzle was watching the Monty Python video. Thanks, Deb!
Isn‚Äôt Elvis‚Äôs middle name spelled ‚ÄúAaron‚Äù?   Somewhat new to this.  Is it a mistake (51 across) or are misspellings in clues fair game?

commentBody:
A PB today that also bested my Monday average by a minute and a half! A little unexpected for a Wednesday, but it was such a pleasant puzzle that I didn't mind.

My only Natick moment was the crossing of ORONO and MOA - I took an educated stab with the O as my final square and lucked into it.

Loved seeing two adorable animals, the MINK and the OTTER, in the puzzle today, and, if I'm not mistaken, there was an ermine clue yesterday too.

Regarding the online arguing - one thing I like about this community is its civility, but I do wonder if it's because of an ideological homogeny about us (as I'd assume most of us also read the NYT) or whether crossword solvers are generally more civil people for whatever reason.

Regardless - a very fine puzzle with a clever theme. Great work!

commentBody:
Yes, BIRD FLU is a really bad flu.  That's the one I've learned to fear recently. But back in the day there was swine flu and that one may have been even worse.  I remember a news article in the NYT about a guy who was sharply criticized at his job for taking a week off due to a case of the regular flu.  The regular flu just wasn't considered serious enough that year to pay any attention to.  Which led me, after reading the article, to write the following:

Swine flu 
Is a fine flu
And it's mine, all mine.
Your flu 
Is a pure flu 
It's true.
But it's dull, sir,
Like an ulcer,
Not sexy like swine,
Like swine flu
That fine flu
That is mine.
Now their flu
Is a fair flu
But they share flu
All the time.
It's the same flu
Not a "name" flu
Like mine.
Don't coddle
Last year's model,
Let them rise,
Let them shine!
While I languish
In the anguish
Of the swine.
In the glory
And the story
Of the swine.

commentBody:
I know it will be a good day if  I can get through a Wednesday puzzle in under 10 minutes

Doubted myself over BLASTOFF when AFAR didn't seem quite right for "HOW Odysseus traveled" 

Confess that the theme escaped me until Deb's column, but an enjoyable puzzle nonetheless

While I've heard of STRAWMAN ARGUMENT, I was wondering if STRAWMAN FALLACY was a real phrase.  But all I had to do was type STRAWM into Google and it popped right up.

The correct phrase is MOVING THE GOALPOSTS, but why quibble?

SLIPPERY SLOPE was the cutest and best-clued of the themers.

This was a fun idea and mildly diverting, but like @Lewis et al I like more challenge on a Wednesday.  Trickier clues surrounding the theme answers would have helped a lot.

Concerning the constructor notes and Scrabble words, I'll have to remember qajaq next time I am dealt a Q, a J, and a blank. It never would have entered my mind to use the blank as another Q.

I thoroughly enjoyed Deb's column today, and it only reinforces my decision to stay off social media. 

A tad easy and breezy for a Wednesday, even though I am not particularly familiar with the subject of logic. (No comments please...). I wasn't sure exactly what STRAWMAN FALLACY was, although the other three themers were very familiar. 

Seeing POTOMAC and POTATO(E) close together made me wonder about the possible portmanteau POTATOMAC. Any suggested definitions?

Don't care to admit all of the obvious things I couldn't remember but just to give you an idea - NATO was one of them. Prepare to be bored in an extensive reply.

[{'commentID': 103960594, 'status': 'approved', 'commentSequence': 103960594, 'userID': 57520630, 'userDisplayName': 'Rich in Atlanta', 'userLocation': 'Clarkston, Georgia', 'userTitle': 'NULL', 'userURL': 'NULL', 'picURL': 'https://s3.amazonaws.com/pimage.timespeople.nytimes.com/avatars/cropped-7d549177eddbfb22f4200275d1e4bd6af9fe7072eb61de39bdcfc68d9809fc1a.jpg', 'commentTitle': '<br\//>', 'commentBody': 'As threatened...

 My answer/clue history search today was for AXEL. I had a couple of things in mind, though I had minimal expectations on one of them. A little background: When I was in college I remember being aware at some point that some of my favorite authors were people who were not native speakers of English, notably Nabokov and Joseph Conrad. So I devoured their works. Anyway, the hero of Conrad's 'Victory' was AXEL Heyst and I wondered if there was any chance that AXEL had ever been clued that way.

Much to my surprise it was - 18 times, between 1956 and 1966. And that was the end of that. "Scandinavian man's name" (or Swedish or Danish) was the only other common clue up until 1969 when the skating jump took over and that became the dominant clue forever after that (with some exceptions).

The other AXEL I had wondered about was AXEL Foley, the lead character in the 'Beverly Hills Cop' films. That was the clue twice - both in the Shortz era. Of the 89 times the answer appeared in the Shortz era, the only other non-skating clue referenced the "Fusco Brothers dog, in comics," but two of the clues were to AXEL Paulsen, who actually invented the jump (and I didn't know that).

 And that covers them all, with two exceptions: "Author Munthe." (1958) and "Wenner-Gren." (1969). Probably would have needed crosses for those. commentBody: Nothing to argue about with this puzzle, a smooth and polished gem. And thank you, Deb, for your comments and the video!

What fun!  28A was the first theme entry I got, and after that they were pretty easy but also very pleasing.  My best Wednesday time (excluding one where I must have entered most of it from a partially completed paper) and my favorite mid-week in recent memory.  I got a non-baseball sports team too, so that's progress for me.

As I never time myself, I have no idea if I solved this much quicker than any other Wednesday, only that I extended my streak to 3, so I must have found it easier than usual.  As always I wonder what day the constructor had in mind. Evan?

Whatever, this week's fun puzzles continue with today's clever theme and lovely clues to those theme answers. We also continue to have a nearly repeated fill with LAMAS.  I'm going to start writing those repeats down, as they are virtually every day, but I can't remember any now.

Very enjoyable puzzle, Evan.

commentBody: I enjoyed the theme. I know what it's like to be a logical fallacy.

Having seen comments about record solving times, I checked my stats and found a ridiculous "best" time listed.  It was under two minutes for a Wednesday puzzle,  I'm not sure I could have transcribed the letters from the answer sheet in under two minutes.  So if anybody knows how such a time might wind up there, I'd appreciate their sharing the insight.  Also, can you reset a particular day's "best" time?

commentBody:
@deb -- Your intro was brilliantly funny.  

This puzzle flew, and to be honest, I don't want my Wednesdays this easy.  I want more wordplay and difficulty in the cluing.  This is a NYT Wednesday, transition into the difficult segment of the week!

I did enjoy the off-the-beaten-path theme, however, and that motivated me to do a bit of scanning about logical fallacies, which awakened terms I haven't thought about in ages: Non-sequitur, red herring, ad hominem, begging the question, hasty generalization, and so on.  Thank you for that, Evan!

I also found the puzzle timely, with NATO as an answer and that overseas meeting going on.

When I went over the puzzle's answers, I saw THERAVEN as a single word, and thought it would be a good name for a pharmaceutical, then saw TREXES also as a single word, thinking it would be a good name for hiking shoes.

commentBody: Record time for a Wednesday for me, though I know some people did in a fraction of that.

and Elke
While the answers to the clues were not difficult, the fun came from  unravelling the fallacies.
I  am reminded of a Chemistry professor ( >55 YRS. ago or so), who used the following example to  demonstrate a correlation/causation fallacy : he  stated that the number of storks in Denmark  correlates directly with the number of births in  Cuba . Therefore storks bring the babies . 
In Cuba, because as all kids in Scandinavia know, storks migrate south in the fall, so thus in the winter, babies in Scandinavia  crawl out from  the cabbages still in the fields.
Probably garbled this- -if somebody remembers it better- go for it :))
This was UDDER fun.
That was such a fabulous theme!  It was fascinating!  After I finished the puzzle, I enjoyed Deb's column and all the links she so kindly provided.  What a fun Wednesday!
I really liked the theme clues.  Soothing mid-week puzzle.  The video clip on arguments was hilarious - I think that was John Cleese in one of the scenes.

It was a rather easy one.  Not easiest Wednesday ever, necessarily, but pretty close.

Favorite clue was for OSHA.  Smiled at that one.  Frowny faced for most of the rest.  Well, ok, not not really.  It was UDDERly fun (why I OTTER...hey MOW, nyuk nyuk nyuk).  I liked the theme entries, particularly CHERRY PICKING..  

Had THE MALL before POTOMAC.  The iffiest entry - TREXES.

It's a busy week and I'm just popping in to catch more people and let you know about the Durham Wordplay lunch on Dec. 14 (Saturday). Say something here if you'd like to come and meet up with more Wordplayers! And/or go to Alan J's website (arjentium.com) and click on "Help and Contact" and give him your basic info; we'll get back to you with the details. Hope to see people there!

Deb wrote:
This puzzle solved very easily in the top half and kicked into challenging gear in the bottom half...

Mine was all top half. I enjoyed the theme clues and answers, but I would have liked a puzzle too.

This puzzle BEGS THE QUESTION (‚ÄúPlease ask me, ask me?  Please!‚Äù):

If it goes by really fast but you enjoyed every second, can it be a great puzzle?

Or would that be CIRCULAR REASONING (‚ÄúRound things are better than square or rectangular things, so oval things must be better than square and rectangular things, too.‚Äù)?
